title: For Sale:  GERMAN "GUILD" SPORTER ON G88 ACTION--NO FFL!
postcontent:
This is a very dainty little German "guild" carbine built on a Gew88 action. For the collector of German hunting guns, or for those who like to hunt with something "different," this is a real find. It's not highly ornate, as some of these guns tend to be, but rather plain; probably sold as a forester's or gamekeeper's gun. There are no proof marks that I can find.

Germany instituted a proof system in 1891, and guns that were in a shop's stock usually bear a mark to indicate they were "grandfathered" in when the law went into effect. This gun doesn't have the mark, leading me to believe the action dates from between 1888 and 1890, i.e., a very early Gew88 action was used to make this sporter before the proof system was set up. There is a proliferatton of marks on the underside of the breech but I have no idea what they mean. They aren’t proof marks. There is a Gothic "T" on one or two parts, and I was told by an advanced collector of German guns that this is a military inspector's mark. It's a virtual certainty this rifle came to the USA as a soldier's trophy after WW2, and of course there are no post-1986 importer's marks.

The Gew88 was a very popular choice for sporters due to its clean lines, trim appearance, and light weight. Many custom guns were made on surplus military actions, and this is one of them. It shows typical first-rate German craftsmanship, though it has no maker's name on it. It was probably assembled around 1910-1920 but it could be earlier, in light of the absence of a proof house stamp.  An identical gun is shown in the 1930 catalog of the famous firm of Burgsmüller und Sohne.

The caliber is “8x57J.” This is the pre-1905 variant of the 8x57 Mauser that uses a 0.318" bullet. Even after the Imperial Army shifted to the larger diameter 0.323" bullet, the older "J" bore was almost always used for hunting guns. Modern production ammunition must NOT be used in this rifle. ONLY ammunition with the 0.318" bullet is safe. European milsurp 8mm Mauser is definitely NOT SAFE in this little rifle. Proper bullets and reloading dies are available but the fact is that this is a handloader's gun.

The 8x57J uses a round nose bullet of 196-200 grains at moderate velocity. Buffalo Arms sells 0.318" bullets in various weights; ordinary 8x57 Mauser cases can be used if you size the case neck to the proper diameter to hold the smaller bullet. All other dimensions are the same as for the ordinary 8x57, and I load this caliber with a die set for the standard round. In deference to its age (all Gew88 actions pre-date 1897) I have kept my handloads about to the .30-30 level, as the Gew88 isn't as strong as the later Mauser 98.

THIS SALE INCLUDES PROPER AMMUNITION FOR THIS RIFLE. I WILL INCLUDE 22 ROUNDS OF LOADED HUNTING AMMUNITION WITH 175-GRAIN JACKETED SOFT POINTS; 20 MORE ROUNDS WITH 196 GRAIN CAST BULLETS; AND 20 CASES READY TO LOAD. BULLETS IN THE PROPER DIAMETER CAN EASILY BE OBTAINED FROM BUFFALO ARMS; A STANDARD 8X57 DIE SET CAN BE USED IF YOU ADD TO IT A NECK-SIZING DIE FOR THE 0.318" BULLET. YOU WILL ALSO GET FOUR (4) OF THE NEEDED CLIPS FOR THE PACKET LOADING SYSTEM. TAKE YOUR NEXT DEER WITH THIS BEAUTIFUL OLD-TIMER!

The pictures show the condition. The stock is in very good shape, with the only serious flaws being a gouge on the left side near the magazine well, and a chip in the toe near the basket-weave butt plate. There are some minor handling and rack dings, but no cracks and no splits. It has a schnabel-type fore-end, very typically Teutonic and very elegant. There is a cheekpiece on the left side of the stock. The usual small German sling swivels are present, but these can be removed and quick-detachable swivels used instead. 

This rifle uses the "packet loading" Mannlicher system. Three of the needed clips are included in the sale as well. These are prevented from dropping out when the last round is chambered by a metal clip that closes the magazine well and keeps out dirt.
It has open sights: a 2-leaf rear sight and a ramped bead front. There is no provision for mounting a scope, nor should there be! (It would desecrate this little gem to scope it. One reason I'm selling it is that my eyes are no longer up to open sights.)

Like most custom hunting guns of the period it has a set trigger for a very light letoff. It can be fired with or without the set trigger being used. Military actions didn't have set triggers: this is one of the modifications made by the gunsmith who assembled it. The safety is the common "flag" type used on Mannlicher and Mauser actions: very positive and with a half-set position to allow safe manipulation of the bolt. There is a clip release in the front of the trigger guard to remove unused ammunition.

Overall length is 37-1/2", with a 13-1/2" length of pull to the front (firing) trigger. The round profile barrel is 16-1/2" long. This short, handy, well balanced carbine would be an ideal rifle for a shooter of small stature. Weight is 5-1/2 pounds, another reason not to use full-house 8x57 ammunition in it!

The bore is very good. Not pristine, but with clean sharp rifling and no pitting. The barrel crown is intact. It shoots better than my eyes are capable of taking advantage of, and it has always been satisfactory for me. No problems hitting an animal at woodland ranges!

As mentioned, all Gew88 actions were manufactured before 1898, so this rifle is a legal "antique" not covered by the never-sufficiently-to-be-cursed Gun Control Act of 1968. It can be sent directly to your street address. Some states may have different laws, but if yours does, contact me BEFORE bidding. I am not an FFL holder, and this gun does not require that one be used. It will be shipped dismounted from the stock to reduce package size, and fully insured. I have had some major problems with the US Postal Service, and will ship via FEDEX.

title: For Sale:  Manurhin PP .32 1955. Very Good Condition! W/Extra Grips - 600 obo
postcontent:
Selling my gorgeous Manurhin (Walther) PP .32. I was going to keep and carry her, but I don't really like carrying anything under .380.

This is a 1955 made, Bavarian State Police issued PP. This was imported to the USA after Walther and Manurhin had their little falling out, so there are X's machined over the Walther name on the side of the firearm, and the Walther name has been machined off the grips. 

This is in very good condition, with backstrap wear (that all of them have) and some carry/holster wear on the slide/edges. When I bought it, the internals looked like it was fired MAYBE 10-20 times over it's lifetime, and I put 50 rounds through it last week with absolutely no problems. Gun shoots great, accurate and fun to shoot. 

Comes with black factory grips, and then green aftermarket, and orange/brown aftermarket. The orange grips I started to cut down the walther logo on the bottom to match how the gun is supposed to look, but I stopped after one side. Grips are factory molded copies dyed different colours from Vintage Gun Grips. 

Asking $600 obo for this. They don't come up for sale very often, but when they do they're pretty expensive. If you've seen these online, you know that it's a great deal because they go for $600-$675 in worse condition, plus shipping fees and FFL charges you're looking at $700+.

Willing to consider all trade offers, but first good cash offer gets it. Please don't try and lowball me. No I will not take $400, and no I will not trade for your $300 handgun. 

Texting REDACTED is the fastest way to get in touch with me if you're interested. 

**I can only have 3 pictures on here, but feel free to text me and I'll send you more.

Thank you for looking!

~ Mike

title: For Sale:  SAR Arms K2 .45 ACP Hi Cap Semi-auto Pistol
postcontent:
***NEW IN BOX***EXCELLENT FIT AND FINISH***FORGED STEEL FRAME***BASED ON TIME TESTED CZ-75 DESIGN***EXCELLENT REVIEW IN NRA'S SEPTEMBER 2013 AMERICAN RIFLEMAN***

These SAR Arms K2 pistols are really nice. In your hand, they feel like a cross between a CZ-75 and a Sig Sauer!!!

If you look closer, you'll see the slide in the frame design which is a characteristic of the CZ-75 and Sig P210.

These K2's are all steel with a forged frame, have a 14+1 capacity, and have excellent quality adjustable sights. Both the front and rear sights are dovetailed and appear to be completely replacable or can be changed out for various aftermarket sights........which is a nice touch.

Comes with one mag, two cleaning rods, sight adjustment tools, lock, and all factory paperwork including manual.

These pistols are manufactured in Turkey by Sarsilmaz (means "unshakable" in Turkish) and were imported into the U.S. by European American Armory (EAA). The magazine is manufactured by Mec-Gar in Italy, the same company that makes mags for Beretta, and Sig-Sauer.

If you are wondering about this pistol, check out the NRA's September 2013 issue of American Rifleman. Long story short, Sarsilmaz is Turkey's largest firearms manufacturer, is thoroughly modern with the most up to date firearms manufacturing materials and processes, and supplies firearms to many of Turkey's governmental agencies including their military.

The NRA had some really positive comments regarding this firearm and reported many things..........such as the single action trigger on their sample broke at 3 lbs, 13.4 ozs and the double action trigger required 9 lbs, 13 ozs to operate. The mags are Italian produced Mec-Gar 14 round Para USA patterned. I'm not sure what this means but I would assume the same mag Para uses would work in this pistol as well. And lastly, the NRA states this pistol is a "solid-shooting platform that should stand up to many tens of thousands of rounds of firing". Sounds like one heck of an endorsement to me!!!


Cash only please, no trades. Due to my work schedule I am not always around, but will do my best to answer emails ASAP. Thanks!

title: For Sale:  Let's Talk About MSRP
postcontent:
MSRP has zero bearing on your gun's value. None whatsoever. Like everything else in life, MSRP is an inflated value set to make it look like you're getting a good deal from a retailer.  Some of you seem to think your gun that cost $500 from budsgunshop is worth $750 because that's what the manufacturer's website says but that's not how things work.

If this is the sort of logic you use then maybe you don't have the mental capacity necessary to safely own firearms.

You're welcome.

postcontent: I'm selling my Remington 1911 R1 Enhanced.  It's a good shooting, reliable gun, and accurage gun.  I switched out the stock trigger pad, which was a bit sloppy, for a Wilson Combat, which fits really nicely.  I also added a Wilson Combat mag well.  The trigger breaks light and crisp.  The sights are really nice.  The rear is a Novak style and is adjustable for elevation, and the front is a well- made red fiber optic that is easy to pick up.  The mag release is really nice, as it is extended, but unobtrusive.  It's very easy to hit, but you won't do it accidentally.  The grip safety and mainspring housing are checkered nicely, and the front strap is serrated.  The hammer and other internals look to be machined, not MIM, which is really nice.  I'm including upgraded magazines from what it came with.  2 will be 8 round Wilson Combat 47DE and 1is an 8 round Novak, which has been just as good as the Wilsons.  I'm also including a Safariland ALS/SLS holster, which alone goes for like $150 or so.  If you're looking for a good 1911 to really shoot, this would be a great choice.
